results.description:
The fork-tailed drongo, also called the common drongo, African drongo, or savanna drongo, is a species of drongo in the family Dicruridae, which are medium-sized passerine birds of the Old World. It is native to the tropics, subtropics and temperate zones of the Afrotropics.
They mimic other bird calls, such as the pearl spotted owlet.
They have a very distinctive forked tail.
They follow mammals to catch insects that have been disturbed in the grass.
They are cleptoparasitic – they steal other birds' food.
They prefer a diet of bees and wasps.
